[This update includes the daily report of MERS-CoV newly confirmed cases and deaths in Saudi Arabia bringing the total numbers of cases and deaths reported by Saudi Arabia to 565 cases of laboratory confirmed MERS-CoV cases including 186 deaths (see [1] above).

The next report (see [2] above) is a WHO update confirming the earlier reported case of MERS-CoV in Jordan. Additional information provided in this update is that the patient had been previously admitted to the same hospital as an earlier confirmed case of MERS-CoV infection, but for health issues not related to MERS-CoV infection. Several days following discharge from this hospital, this individual had onset of symptoms compatible with MERS-CoV infection. Hence, this case would be considered as a nosocomial associated infection. According to the WHO update for 28 May 2014, there have now been 636 laboratory confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV officially reported to WHO including 193 deaths, including cases reported by Saudi Arabia through 18 May 2014. Since 18 May 2014 there have been an additional 34 cases including 17 deaths reported by Saudi Arabia, and 2 cases reported in the press by the Iranian MOH. Inclusion of these additional cases and deaths would bring the global tally of laboratory confirmed MERS-CoV infections to 672 cases including 210 deaths.

A map showing the locations of recently reported cases and deaths in Saudi Arabia can be seen at the Ministry of Health URL above. For a map of Jordan, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2504495,91. - Mod.MPP]
